84: /**
85:  * A client that consumes records from a Kafka cluster.
86:  * <p>
87:  * This client transparently handles the failure of Kafka brokers, and transparently adapts as topic partitions
88:  * it fetches migrate within the cluster. This client also interacts with the broker to allow groups of
89:  * consumers to load balance consumption using <a href="#consumergroups">consumer groups</a>.
90:  * <p>
91:  * The consumer maintains TCP connections to the necessary brokers to fetch data.
92:  * Failure to close the consumer after use will leak these connections.
93:  * The consumer is not thread-safe. See <a href="#multithreaded">Multi-threaded Processing</a> for more details.
94:  *
95:  * <h3>Cross-Version Compatibility</h3>
96:  * This client can communicate with brokers that are version 0.10.0 or newer. Older or newer brokers may not support
97:  * certain features. For example, 0.10.0 brokers do not support offsetsForTimes, because this feature was added
98:  * in version 0.10.1. You will receive an {@link org.apache.kafka.common.errors.UnsupportedVersionException}
99:  * when invoking an API that is not available on the running broker version.
100:  * <p>
101:  *
102:  * <h3>Offsets and Consumer Position</h3>
103:  * Kafka maintains a numerical offset for each record in a partition. This offset acts as a unique identifier of
104:  * a record within that partition, and also denotes the position of the consumer in the partition. For example, a consumer
105:  * which is at position 5 has consumed records with offsets 0 through 4 and will next receive the record with offset 5. There
106:  * are actually two notions of position relevant to the user of the consumer:
107:  * <p>
108:  * The {@link #position(TopicPartition) position} of the consumer gives the offset of the next record that will be given
109:  * out. It will be one larger than the highest offset the consumer has seen in that partition. It automatically advances
110:  * every time the consumer receives messages in a call to {@link #poll(Duration)}.
111:  * <p>
112:  * The {@link #commitSync() committed position} is the last offset that has been stored securely. Should the
113:  * process fail and restart, this is the offset that the consumer will recover to. The consumer can either automatically commit
114:  * offsets periodically; or it can choose to control this committed position manually by calling one of the commit APIs
115:  * (e.g. {@link #commitSync() commitSync} and {@link #commitAsync(OffsetCommitCallback) commitAsync}).
116:  * <p>
117:  * This distinction gives the consumer control over when a record is considered consumed. It is discussed in further
118:  * detail below.
119:  *
120:  * <h3><a name="consumergroups">Consumer Groups and Topic Subscriptions</a></h3>
121:  *
122:  * Kafka uses the concept of <i>consumer groups</i> to allow a pool of processes to divide the work of consuming and
123:  * processing records. These processes can either be running on the same machine or they can be
124:  * distributed over many machines to provide scalability and fault tolerance for processing. All consumer instances
125:  * sharing the same {@code group.id} will be part of the same consumer group.
126:  * <p>
127:  * Each consumer in a group can dynamically set the list of topics it wants to subscribe to through one of the
128:  * {@link #subscribe(Collection, ConsumerRebalanceListener) subscribe} APIs. Kafka will deliver each message in the
129:  * subscribed topics to one process in each consumer group. This is achieved by balancing the partitions between all
130:  * members in the consumer group so that each partition is assigned to exactly one consumer in the group. So if there
131:  * is a topic with four partitions, and a consumer group with two processes, each process would consume from two partitions.
132:  * <p>
133:  * Membership in a consumer group is maintained dynamically: if a process fails, the partitions assigned to it will
134:  * be reassigned to other consumers in the same group. Similarly, if a new consumer joins the group, partitions will be moved
135:  * from existing consumers to the new one. This is known as <i>rebalancing</i> the group and is discussed in more
136:  * detail <a href="#failuredetection">below</a>. Group rebalancing is also used when new partitions are added
137:  * to one of the subscribed topics or when a new topic matching a {@link #subscribe(Pattern, ConsumerRebalanceListener) subscribed regex}
138:  * is created. The group will automatically detect the new partitions through periodic metadata refreshes and
139:  * assign them to members of the group.
140:  * <p>
141:  * Conceptually you can think of a consumer group as being a single logical subscriber that happens to be made up of
142:  * multiple processes. As a multi-subscriber system, Kafka naturally supports having any number of consumer groups for a
143:  * given topic without duplicating data (additional consumers are actually quite cheap).
144:  * <p>
145:  * This is a slight generalization of the functionality that is common in messaging systems. To get semantics similar to
146:  * a queue in a traditional messaging system all processes would be part of a single consumer group and hence record
147:  * delivery would be balanced over the group like with a queue. Unlike a traditional messaging system, though, you can
148:  * have multiple such groups. To get semantics similar to pub-sub in a traditional messaging system each process would
149:  * have its own consumer group, so each process would subscribe to all the records published to the topic.
150:  * <p>
151:  * In addition, when group reassignment happens automatically, consumers can be notified through a {@link ConsumerRebalanceListener},
152:  * which allows them to finish necessary application-level logic such as state cleanup, manual offset
153:  * commits, etc. See <a href="#rebalancecallback">Storing Offsets Outside Kafka</a> for more details.
154:  * <p>
155:  * It is also possible for the consumer to <a href="#manualassignment">manually assign</a> specific partitions
156:  * (similar to the older "simple" consumer) using {@link #assign(Collection)}. In this case, dynamic partition
157:  * assignment and consumer group coordination will be disabled.
158:  *
159:  * <h3><a name="failuredetection">Detecting Consumer Failures</a></h3>
160:  *
161:  * After subscribing to a set of topics, the consumer will automatically join the group when {@link #poll(Duration)} is
162:  * invoked. The poll API is designed to ensure consumer liveness. As long as you continue to call poll, the consumer
163:  * will stay in the group and continue to receive messages from the partitions it was assigned. Underneath the covers,
164:  * the consumer sends periodic heartbeats to the server. If the consumer crashes or is unable to send heartbeats for
165:  * a duration of {@code session.timeout.ms}, then the consumer will be considered dead and its partitions will
166:  * be reassigned.
167:  * <p>
168:  * It is also possible that the consumer could encounter a "livelock" situation where it is continuing
169:  * to send heartbeats, but no progress is being made. To prevent the consumer from holding onto its partitions
170:  * indefinitely in this case, we provide a liveness detection mechanism using the {@code max.poll.interval.ms}
171:  * setting. Basically if you don't call poll at least as frequently as the configured max interval,
172:  * then the client will proactively leave the group so that another consumer can take over its partitions. When this happens,
173:  * you may see an offset commit failure (as indicated by a {@link CommitFailedException} thrown from a call to {@link #commitSync()}).
174:  * This is a safety mechanism which guarantees that only active members of the group are able to commit offsets.
175:  * So to stay in the group, you must continue to call poll.
176:  * <p>
177:  * The consumer provides two configuration settings to control the behavior of the poll loop:
178:  * <ol>
179:  *     <li><code>max.poll.interval.ms</code>: By increasing the interval between expected polls, you can give
180:  *     the consumer more time to handle a batch of records returned from {@link #poll(Duration)}. The drawback
181:  *     is that increasing this value may delay a group rebalance since the consumer will only join the rebalance
182:  *     inside the call to poll. You can use this setting to bound the time to finish a rebalance, but
183:  *     you risk slower progress if the consumer cannot actually call {@link #poll(Duration) poll} often enough.</li>
184:  *     <li><code>max.poll.records</code>: Use this setting to limit the total records returned from a single
185:  *     call to poll. This can make it easier to predict the maximum that must be handled within each poll
186:  *     interval. By tuning this value, you may be able to reduce the poll interval, which will reduce the
187:  *     impact of group rebalancing.</li>
188:  * </ol>
189:  * <p>
190:  * For use cases where message processing time varies unpredictably, neither of these options may be sufficient.
191:  * The recommended way to handle these cases is to move message processing to another thread, which allows
192:  * the consumer to continue calling {@link #poll(Duration) poll} while the processor is still working.
193:  * Some care must be taken to ensure that committed offsets do not get ahead of the actual position.
194:  * Typically, you must disable automatic commits and manually commit processed offsets for records only after the
195:  * thread has finished handling them (depending on the delivery semantics you need).
196:  * Note also that you will need to {@link #pause(Collection) pause} the partition so that no new records are received
197:  * from poll until after thread has finished handling those previously returned.
198:  *
199:  * <h3>Usage Examples</h3>
200:  * The consumer APIs offer flexibility to cover a variety of consumption use cases. Here are some examples to
201:  * demonstrate how to use them.
202:  *
203:  * <h4>Automatic Offset Committing</h4>
204:  * This example demonstrates a simple usage of Kafka's consumer api that relies on automatic offset committing.
205:  * <p>
206:  * <pre>
207:  *     Properties props = new Properties();
208:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;bootstrap.servers&quot;, &quot;localhost:9092&quot;);
209:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;group.id&quot;, &quot;test&quot;);
210:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;enable.auto.commit&quot;, &quot;true&quot;);
211:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;auto.commit.interval.ms&quot;, &quot;1000&quot;);
212:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;key.deserializer&quot;, &quot;org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer&quot;);
213:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;value.deserializer&quot;, &quot;org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer&quot;);
214:  *     KafkaConsumer&lt;String, String&gt; consumer = new KafkaConsumer&lt;&gt;(props);
215:  *     consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList(&quot;foo&quot;, &quot;bar&quot;));
216:  *     while (true) {
217:  *         ConsumerRecords&lt;String, String&gt; records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));
218:  *         for (ConsumerRecord&lt;String, String&gt; record : records)
219:  *             System.out.printf(&quot;offset = %d, key = %s, value = %s%n&quot;, record.offset(), record.key(), record.value());
220:  *     }
221:  * </pre>
222:  *
223:  * The connection to the cluster is bootstrapped by specifying a list of one or more brokers to contact using the
224:  * configuration {@code >bootstrap.servers}. This list is just used to discover the rest of the brokers in the
225:  * cluster and need not be an exhaustive list of servers in the cluster (though you may want to specify more than one in
226:  * case there are servers down when the client is connecting).
227:  * <p>
228:  * Setting {@code enable.auto.commit} means that offsets are committed automatically with a frequency controlled by
229:  * the config {@code auto.commit.interval.ms}.
230:  * <p>
231:  * In this example the consumer is subscribing to the topics <i>foo</i> and <i>bar</i> as part of a group of consumers
232:  * called <i>test</i> as configured with {@code group.id}.
233:  * <p>
234:  * The deserializer settings specify how to turn bytes into objects. For example, by specifying string deserializers, we
235:  * are saying that our record's key and value will just be simple strings.
236:  *
237:  * <h4>Manual Offset Control</h4>
238:  *
239:  * Instead of relying on the consumer to periodically commit consumed offsets, users can also control when records
240:  * should be considered as consumed and hence commit their offsets. This is useful when the consumption of the messages
241:  * is coupled with some processing logic and hence a message should not be considered as consumed until it is completed processing.
242: 
243:  * <p>
244:  * <pre>
245:  *     Properties props = new Properties();
246:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;bootstrap.servers&quot;, &quot;localhost:9092&quot;);
247:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;group.id&quot;, &quot;test&quot;);
248:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;enable.auto.commit&quot;, &quot;false&quot;);
249:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;key.deserializer&quot;, &quot;org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer&quot;);
250:  *     props.setProperty(&quot;value.deserializer&quot;, &quot;org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer&quot;);
251:  *     KafkaConsumer&lt;String, String&gt; consumer = new KafkaConsumer&lt;&gt;(props);
252:  *     consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList(&quot;foo&quot;, &quot;bar&quot;));
253:  *     final int minBatchSize = 200;
254:  *     List&lt;ConsumerRecord&lt;String, String&gt;&gt; buffer = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
255:  *     while (true) {
256:  *         ConsumerRecords&lt;String, String&gt; records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));
257:  *         for (ConsumerRecord&lt;String, String&gt; record : records) {
258:  *             buffer.add(record);
259:  *         }
260:  *         if (buffer.size() &gt;= minBatchSize) {
261:  *             insertIntoDb(buffer);
262:  *             consumer.commitSync();
263:  *             buffer.clear();
264:  *         }
265:  *     }
266:  * </pre>
267:  *
268:  * In this example we will consume a batch of records and batch them up in memory. When we have enough records
269:  * batched, we will insert them into a database. If we allowed offsets to auto commit as in the previous example, records
270:  * would be considered consumed after they were returned to the user in {@link #poll(Duration) poll}. It would then be
271:  * possible
272:  * for our process to fail after batching the records, but before they had been inserted into the database.
273:  * <p>
274:  * To avoid this, we will manually commit the offsets only after the corresponding records have been inserted into the
275:  * database. This gives us exact control of when a record is considered consumed. This raises the opposite possibility:
276:  * the process could fail in the interval after the insert into the database but before the commit (even though this
277:  * would likely just be a few milliseconds, it is a possibility). In this case the process that took over consumption
278:  * would consume from last committed offset and would repeat the insert of the last batch of data. Used in this way
279:  * Kafka provides what is often called "at-least-once" delivery guarantees, as each record will likely be delivered one
280:  * time but in failure cases could be duplicated.
281:  * <p>
282:  * <b>Note: Using automatic offset commits can also give you "at-least-once" delivery, but the requirement is that
283:  * you must consume all data returned from each call to {@link #poll(Duration)} before any subsequent calls, or before
284:  * {@link #close() closing} the consumer. If you fail to do either of these, it is possible for the committed offset
285:  * to get ahead of the consumed position, which results in missing records. The advantage of using manual offset
286:  * control is that you have direct control over when a record is considered "consumed."</b>
287:  * <p>
288:  * The above example uses {@link #commitSync() commitSync} to mark all received records as committed. In some cases
289:  * you may wish to have even finer control over which records have been committed by specifying an offset explicitly.
290:  * In the example below we commit offset after we finish handling the records in each partition.
291:  * <p>
292:  * <pre>
293:  *     try {
294:  *         while(running) {
295:  *             ConsumerRecords&lt;String, String&gt; records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(Long.MAX_VALUE));
296:  *             for (TopicPartition partition : records.partitions()) {
297:  *                 List&lt;ConsumerRecord&lt;String, String&gt;&gt; partitionRecords = records.records(partition);
298:  *                 for (ConsumerRecord&lt;String, String&gt; record : partitionRecords) {
299:  *                     System.out.println(record.offset() + &quot;: &quot; + record.value());
300:  *                 }
